    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="144"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A3/1861</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Japanese Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Saito</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-30">December 30,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: The receipt is acknowledged of Your
                    Excellency’s note, dated December 28, 1936, in which you state that the
                    Government of Japan has decided to invoke Article 21 of the London Naval Treaty,
                    1930, in order to retain 15,598 tons of submarines in excess of the maximum
                    tonnage which is permitted in this category under the terms of Article 16,
                    paragraph 1, of the London Naval Treaty, in order to meet the requirements of
                    the national security of Japan.</p>
                <p>In view of the decision of the Government of Japan to invoke Article 21, this
                    Government will exercise its right under this Article to retain a proportionate
                    amount of tonnage in the submarine category.</p>
                <p>On December 31, 1936, this Government will have 15,230 tons of submarines in
                    excess of the maximum tonnage which is permitted under the terms of Article 16,
                    paragraph 1, of the London Naval Treaty, 1930.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. <hi rend="smallcaps">Walton Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
